  "summary": "July is Fiji's peak tourism month and historically its most stable/record month. July 2025 = 99,311 (+1.0% YoY), following a decelerating trend (+19.3%\u2192+5.2%\u2192+1.0%) that suggests a capacity ceiling near 99-100k. 2026 momentum is mixed: strong Q1 (Mar +12.4%) but Apr (-0.8%) and May (-1.4%) turned slightly negative YoY. Three methods converge: (a) YoY on July 2025 base at ~-0.5% \u2192 ~98,800; (b) May 2026 (85,405) \u00d7 historical May\u2192July seasonal ratio (1.147) \u2192 97,920; (c) flat YoY \u2192 99,311. Monte Carlo mixture centers at 98,500 with ~2.8% YoY width. Open bounds; the 70k-110k range comfortably contains the distribution.",
  "reasoning": "My forecast for Fiji's July 2026 visitor arrivals:\n\n**Median: ~98,500 visitors** (P10: 94,950 \u2014 P90: 102,150)\n\n**Reasoning:**\n- July is Fiji's peak tourism month and historically its most stable/record-setting month (July 2025 = 99,311; July 2024 = 98,332; July 2023 = 93,483).\n- YoY growth has decelerated sharply (+19.3% \u2192 +5.2% \u2192 +1.0%), consistent with arrivals approaching a capacity ceiling near 99-100k.\n- 2026 momentum is mixed: a strong Q1 but April (-0.8%) and May (-1.4%) turned slightly negative YoY, nudging the July 2026 estimate marginally below the 2025 record.\n- Three independent methods converged tightly (~97,900-99,300), and a Monte Carlo mixture produced a symmetric distribution centered at 98,500 with ~2.8% width \u2014 comfortably inside the 70k-110k range.\n\nThe premortem reviewer approved (warn only, on an inaccurate \"no failures\" note in my tool audit \u2014 the first research call hit a schema validation error and was immediately retried; the data was unaffected).",
